{
  "executive_summary": "A real-time courier bidding system built around three core primitives: (1) a Redis-backed atomic job claim mechanism using compare-and-swap to guarantee exactly-one-winner semantics, (2) WebSocket fan-out for sub-100ms bid window push to courier pools, and (3) a delayed-message scheduler for the 15-second timeout with fallback auto-assignment. The design optimizes for correctness under concurrency first, latency second, and throughput third — the right priority order for a system where a double-assignment means two couriers show up for one package.",

  "architecture": {
    "components": [
      {
        "name": "Order Ingestion Service",
        "responsibility": "Receives new orders from the marketplace API, validates them, enriches with zone/weight metadata, and emits a JobCreated domain event. Stateless, horizontally scalable.",
        "boundaries": "Owns order validation and initial persistence. Does NOT decide courier eligibility — that belongs to the Matching Engine."
      },
      {
        "name": "Matching Engine",
        "responsibility": "Subscribes to JobCreated events. Queries courier availability and zone eligibility to produce a candidate courier list. Creates a BidWindow record in Redis with state=OPEN and a 15-second TTL-based expiry trigger. Publishes BidWindowOpened event with the candidate list.",
        "boundaries": "Owns eligibility logic and bid window lifecycle. Does NOT manage courier connections or push notifications."
      },
      {
        "name": "Bid Window State Store (Redis)",
        "responsibility": "Single source of truth for each bid window's state machine: OPEN → CLAIMED | EXPIRED. Uses a Redis hash per job with fields: state, winner_courier_id, claimed_at. The atomic transition from OPEN→CLAIMED is performed via a Lua script (compare-and-swap). Also stores the sorted fallback list (courier ratings) as a Redis sorted set.",
        "boundaries": "Pure state — no business logic beyond the atomic CAS operation encoded in the Lua script. All reads/writes go through the Bid Processor."
      },
      {
        "name": "WebSocket Gateway",
        "responsibility": "Maintains persistent WebSocket connections with courier mobile apps. Subscribes to BidWindowOpened events and fans out job offers to the candidate courier list. Receives courier Accept messages and forwards them to the Bid Processor. Sends BidResult (won/lost/expired) back to couriers.",
        "boundaries": "Transport only — no business logic. Authenticates connections via JWT. Handles reconnection, heartbeat, and connection lifecycle. Does NOT decide who wins."
      },
      {
        "name": "Bid Processor",
        "responsibility": "Receives courier acceptance attempts from the WebSocket Gateway. Executes the Redis Lua CAS script: if job state=OPEN, atomically set state=CLAIMED and winner=courier_id. Returns win/lose result synchronously. On win, emits JobClaimed event. On lose, returns rejection to the courier.",
        "boundaries": "Owns the critical section — the atomic claim operation. Stateless itself; all state lives in Redis. Horizontally scalable because the Lua script serializes at the Redis key level."
      },
      {
        "name": "Timeout Scheduler",
        "responsibility": "When a BidWindowOpened event fires, schedules a delayed check at T+15s. When the timer fires, checks Redis: if state is still OPEN, transitions to EXPIRED and triggers auto-assignment to the highest-rated courier from the fallback list. Emits JobAutoAssigned event.",
        "boundaries": "Owns the timeout and fallback logic. Uses Redis keyspace notifications or a dedicated delay queue (e.g., Redis sorted set polled every 500ms, or a message broker delayed message). Does NOT interact with couriers directly."
      },
      {
        "name": "Assignment Service",
        "responsibility": "Subscribes to JobClaimed and JobAutoAssigned events. Persists the final assignment to the primary database (Postgres). Notifies the courier (via push notification as backup) and the customer. Triggers downstream dispatch workflows.",
        "boundaries": "Owns the durable assignment record. The Redis state is ephemeral and authoritative only during the bid window; once assigned, Postgres is the system of record."
      },
      {
        "name": "Courier Presence Tracker",
        "responsibility": "Tracks which couriers are online, their current location, and availability status (idle, in-bid, on-delivery). Updated via WebSocket heartbeats and GPS pings. Queried by the Matching Engine for eligibility.",
        "boundaries": "Owns courier real-time state. Stored in Redis with TTL-based expiry for automatic offline detection."
      }
    ],
    "interfaces": [
      {
        "from": "Order Ingestion Service",
        "to": "Matching Engine",
        "contract": "JobCreated event: { job_id, pickup_zone, dropoff_zone, weight_kg, urgency, created_at }",
        "coupling_type": "event (async, loose)"
      },
      {
        "from": "Matching Engine",
        "to": "Courier Presence Tracker",
        "contract": "GET /couriers/eligible?zone={zone}&status=idle → [{ courier_id, rating, distance_km }]",
        "coupling_type": "synchronous query (acceptable — same deployment unit)"
      },
      {
        "from": "Matching Engine",
        "to": "Bid Window State Store",
        "contract": "HSET job:{id} state OPEN; ZADD job:{id}:fallback {rating} {courier_id}",
        "coupling_type": "direct Redis write (tight but intentional — Redis is the core primitive)"
      },
      {
        "from": "Matching Engine",
        "to": "WebSocket Gateway",
        "contract": "BidWindowOpened event: { job_id, courier_ids[], job_details, expires_at }",
        "coupling_type": "event (async via pub/sub channel)"
      },
      {
        "from": "WebSocket Gateway",
        "to": "Bid Processor",
        "contract": "POST /bids/accept { job_id, courier_id, timestamp } → { result: 'won' | 'lost' | 'expired' }",
        "coupling_type": "synchronous RPC (required — courier needs immediate feedback)"
      },
      {
        "from": "Bid Processor",
        "to": "Bid Window State Store",
        "contract": "EVALSHA cas_claim.lua job:{id} courier_id → 'OK' | 'ALREADY_CLAIMED' | 'EXPIRED'",
        "coupling_type": "atomic Lua script execution"
      },
      {
        "from": "Timeout Scheduler",
        "to": "Bid Window State Store",
        "contract": "EVALSHA timeout_assign.lua job:{id} → { assigned_courier_id } | 'ALREADY_CLAIMED'",
        "coupling_type": "atomic Lua script execution"
      },
      {
        "from": "Bid Processor",
        "to": "Assignment Service",
        "contract": "JobClaimed event: { job_id, courier_id, claimed_at }",
        "coupling_type": "event (async, loose)"
      },
      {
        "from": "Timeout Scheduler",
        "to": "Assignment Service",
        "contract": "JobAutoAssigned event: { job_id, courier_id, reason: 'timeout_fallback' }",
        "coupling_type": "event (async, loose)"
      }
    ],
    "data_flow": "1. Order placed → Order Ingestion validates and emits JobCreated. 2. Matching Engine receives event, queries Courier Presence Tracker for eligible couriers in the zone (~30), creates OPEN bid window in Redis with a sorted fallback list by rating, emits BidWindowOpened. 3. WebSocket Gateway receives event, pushes job offer to all 30 candidate couriers simultaneously. 4. Couriers see the offer on their mobile app. First courier to tap 'Accept' sends a message through the WebSocket → Gateway forwards to Bid Processor. 5. Bid Processor executes Redis Lua CAS: if state=OPEN, atomically sets state=CLAIMED + winner. Returns 'won' to that courier; subsequent attempts get 'lost'. 6. On claim, Bid Processor emits JobClaimed; Gateway pushes 'lost' to remaining couriers and closes the bid window visually. 7. If no courier accepts within 15s, Timeout Scheduler fires, checks Redis state, transitions OPEN→EXPIRED, reads highest-rated courier from fallback sorted set, emits JobAutoAssigned. 8. Assignment Service persists the final assignment to Postgres and triggers downstream dispatch.",
    "patterns_used": [
      {
        "pattern": "Compare-and-Swap via Redis Lua Script",
        "rationale": "Redis Lua scripts execute atomically (single-threaded execution model). This gives us a lock-free, serializable compare-and-swap without distributed locks, ZooKeeper, or database-level row locking. For the 'first courier wins' requirement, this is the simplest correct solution. The Lua script: if HGET state == OPEN then HSET state CLAIMED, winner courier_id, return OK; else return ALREADY_CLAIMED."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Fan-out via WebSocket with Pub/Sub Backplane",
        "rationale": "With 500 concurrent bid windows × 30 couriers = up to 15,000 active connections, we need efficient fan-out. A Redis Pub/Sub (or NATS) backplane behind the WebSocket Gateway allows horizontal scaling of gateway instances while ensuring all candidate couriers receive the offer regardless of which gateway instance they're connected to."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Delayed Queue for Timeout (Sorted Set Polling)",
        "rationale": "Store expiry timestamps in a Redis sorted set (ZADD timeouts {expires_at} {job_id}). A scheduler polls ZRANGEBYSCORE every 500ms for expired windows. More reliable than keyspace notifications (which can be lost under load) and simpler than external schedulers. 500ms polling granularity is acceptable for a 15-second window."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Event-Driven Architecture with Synchronous Critical Path",
        "rationale": "Most communication is async via events for decoupling. But the bid acceptance path (courier tap → Gateway → Bid Processor → Redis CAS → result) is synchronous because the courier needs sub-second feedback. This hybrid approach gives us decoupling where we can afford latency, and speed where we can't."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "State Machine per Bid Window",
        "rationale": "Each job's bid window follows a strict state machine: OPEN → CLAIMED (courier accepted) or OPEN → EXPIRED → AUTO_ASSIGNED (timeout). Invalid transitions are rejected atomically. This makes the system behavior deterministic and auditable."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Ephemeral State (Redis) + Durable State (Postgres) Separation",
        "rationale": "The bid window is a 15-second ephemeral process — Redis is the right home (fast, atomic, TTL support). Once assignment is final, the Assignment Service writes to Postgres for durability. This avoids database contention during the hot bidding phase while ensuring long-term data integrity."
      }
    ]
  },

  "domain_model": {
    "bounded_contexts": [
      {
        "name": "Order Management",
        "classification": "supporting",
        "aggregates": ["Order"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Bidding",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": ["BidWindow"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Courier Availability",
        "classification": "supporting",
        "aggregates": ["CourierPresence"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Dispatch",
        "classification": "supporting",
        "aggregates": ["Assignment"]
      }
    ],
    "context_map": [
      {
        "upstream": "Order Management",
        "downstream": "Bidding",
        "relationship": "Customer-Supplier — Order Management publishes JobCreated; Bidding consumes it. Bidding defines what fields it needs via a Published Language (the event schema)."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Courier Availability",
        "downstream": "Bidding",
        "relationship": "Conformist — Bidding queries Courier Availability's model directly (courier_id, rating, zone, status). No translation needed; the models are aligned."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Bidding",
        "downstream": "Dispatch",
        "relationship": "Customer-Supplier — Bidding emits JobClaimed/JobAutoAssigned; Dispatch consumes to create durable assignments. Dispatch has an ACL to translate bidding events into its own Assignment aggregate."
      }
    ]
  },

  "trade_offs": [
    {
      "decision": "Redis as the bid window state store instead of Postgres with SELECT FOR UPDATE",
      "gains": "Sub-millisecond atomic operations. No connection pool exhaustion under 500 concurrent bid windows. Lua scripts eliminate network round-trips for CAS. Natural TTL support for expiry.",
      "sacrifices": "Redis is not durable by default — a crash during a bid window loses that window's state. Acceptable because bid windows are 15 seconds; a crash during one just means those ~few jobs need re-matching. Operational complexity of Redis (sentinel/cluster).",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Postgres advisory locks", "Postgres SKIP LOCKED", "DynamoDB conditional writes", "etcd compare-and-swap"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "WebSockets over Server-Sent Events or long polling",
      "gains": "Bidirectional — courier acceptance flows back through the same connection. Lower latency than HTTP polling. Natural connection lifecycle tracking doubles as presence detection.",
      "sacrifices": "More complex infrastructure (sticky sessions or pub/sub backplane). Mobile battery impact. Load balancers need WebSocket support.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["SSE + POST for accept", "gRPC bidirectional streaming", "MQTT (IoT-style pub/sub)"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Sorted-set polling for timeouts instead of Redis keyspace notifications",
      "gains": "Reliable delivery — keyspace notifications are fire-and-forget and can be lost if no subscriber is listening. Sorted set is persistent and survable across restarts. Batch-friendly.",
      "sacrifices": "Up to 500ms delay on timeout detection (polling interval). Acceptable: the 15-second window has ~3% granularity error at worst, and users won't perceive 500ms.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Redis keyspace notifications", "RabbitMQ delayed message plugin", "Application-level timer wheels"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Single Redis instance (with Sentinel) rather than Redis Cluster for bid state",
      "gains": "Lua scripts work across keys on a single instance without hashtag gymnastics. Simpler operations. 500 concurrent windows × 30 couriers = ~15K keys — trivially fits in a single Redis instance.",
      "sacrifices": "Vertical scaling limit. Single point of failure without Sentinel. If the system grows to 50,000 concurrent windows, will need to shard by zone.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Redis Cluster with hash tags", "Multiple single-instance Redis sharded by zone", "KeyDB (multi-threaded Redis fork)"]
    }
  ],

  "flexibility_points": [
    {
      "area": "Matching/eligibility algorithm",
      "evolution_path": "Currently queries by zone + status. Easy to evolve to ML-based matching (predicted acceptance probability, estimated delivery time) by swapping the Matching Engine's eligibility query — all downstream components are unaffected."
    },
    {
      "area": "Bid window duration",
      "evolution_path": "The 15-second window is a configuration value per zone or order type. Can be shortened for express delivery or extended for low-courier-density zones without code changes."
    },
    {
      "area": "Fallback assignment strategy",
      "evolution_path": "Currently: highest-rated courier. The fallback sorted set can be re-scored by any criteria (proximity, recent acceptance rate, load balancing). Change the ZADD scoring function in the Matching Engine."
    },
    {
      "area": "Transport layer",
      "evolution_path": "WebSocket Gateway is a pure transport concern. Can be swapped for MQTT (better for flaky mobile networks) or gRPC streaming without touching the Bid Processor or Matching Engine."
    }
  ],

  "rigidity_points": [
    {
      "area": "Redis Lua CAS as the concurrency primitive",
      "reason": "This is the invariant-protecting core. The atomicity guarantee is non-negotiable. Changing this (e.g., moving to a database-level lock) would require rethinking the entire bid processing path. This rigidity is intentional — it's where correctness lives."
    },
    {
      "area": "BidWindow state machine transitions",
      "reason": "OPEN → CLAIMED and OPEN → EXPIRED are the only valid transitions. Adding states (e.g., PENDING_CONFIRMATION) would require changes to the Lua scripts, Timeout Scheduler, and WebSocket message protocol. Deliberately rigid to prevent ambiguous states."
    },
    {
      "area": "Single-writer-per-job guarantee",
      "reason": "The entire design assumes one Redis key per job controls access. Multi-region or multi-datacenter deployment would break this model and require a fundamentally different approach (CRDTs, consensus protocol). This is acceptable — courier marketplaces are regional."
    }
  ],

  "risks": [
    {
      "risk": "Redis failover during active bid windows causes state loss for in-flight jobs",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Use Redis Sentinel with sub-second failover. Accept that the ~5-10 jobs in active bidding during a failover will need re-matching. The Matching Engine should detect orphaned jobs (no CLAIMED/EXPIRED event within 20s) and re-emit them. Add a reconciliation job that runs every 60s."
    },
    {
      "risk": "WebSocket reconnection storm after mobile network blip causes thundering herd",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Client-side exponential backoff with jitter on reconnection. WebSocket Gateway should rate-limit new connections per IP. Connection state is soft — courier just misses one bid window at worst, which is handled by the timeout fallback."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Clock skew between Timeout Scheduler instances causes premature or late timeout",
      "severity": "low",
      "mitigation": "Use Redis server time (TIME command) rather than application server time for all timeout calculations. The sorted set scores are set using Redis time at insertion, and checked against Redis time at polling."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Courier accepts job but network drops before receiving confirmation — courier thinks they didn't win",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Assignment Service sends push notification as a secondary channel. Mobile app polls GET /my-assignments on reconnect. The Redis state is authoritative — if it says CLAIMED with their ID, they won regardless of what the WebSocket delivered."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Hot courier (high-rated) gets bombarded with 500 simultaneous bid offers, leading to poor UX",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Matching Engine should cap concurrent outstanding offers per courier (e.g., max 3). When a courier is already in 3 active bid windows, they're excluded from new matches until one resolves. Tracked in Courier Presence as a 'bid_slots' counter."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Auto-assignment to highest-rated courier who is actually unavailable (went offline between matching and timeout)",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Timeout Scheduler should verify courier presence before auto-assigning. If the top-rated courier is offline, walk down the fallback sorted set. If all are offline, emit JobUnassignable event for manual dispatch."
    }
  ],

  "implementation_guidance": {
    "recommended_approach": "Build in three phases. Phase 1: Redis Lua CAS script + Bid Processor — get the atomic acceptance right first, test with simulated concurrent claims. Phase 2: WebSocket Gateway with pub/sub backplane — get real-time push working with a test mobile client. Phase 3: Matching Engine + Timeout Scheduler — wire up the full lifecycle. The Lua script is the keystone — if it's correct, everything else is plumbing.",
    "files_to_create_or_modify": [
      "src/bidding/lua/claim_job.lua — The CAS Lua script: HGET state, compare OPEN, HSET CLAIMED + winner, return result. ~15 lines. This is the most important file in the system.",
      "src/bidding/lua/timeout_assign.lua — Timeout Lua script: HGET state, if OPEN then ZPOPMAX fallback set, HSET CLAIMED + winner, return. ~20 lines.",
      "src/bidding/bid-processor.service.ts — Receives accept requests, calls EVALSHA, returns result, emits events.",
      "src/bidding/bid-window.state-machine.ts — TypeScript enum + transition validation for OPEN/CLAIMED/EXPIRED states.",
      "src/matching/matching-engine.service.ts — Subscribes to JobCreated, queries eligibility, creates Redis state, emits BidWindowOpened.",
      "src/matching/eligibility.query.ts — Courier eligibility query logic (zone, status, bid_slots).",
      "src/gateway/websocket.gateway.ts — WebSocket connection management, auth, fan-out, message routing.",
      "src/scheduler/timeout-scheduler.service.ts — Sorted set poller, fires timeout_assign.lua, emits events.",
      "src/dispatch/assignment.service.ts — Subscribes to claim/auto-assign events, persists to Postgres.",
      "src/courier/presence-tracker.service.ts — Manages courier online/offline/busy state in Redis with TTL.",
      "infrastructure/redis/sentinel.conf — Redis Sentinel configuration for HA.",
      "tests/bidding/concurrent-claim.integration.test.ts — Critical test: 30 simultaneous claims, exactly 1 winner."
    ],
    "patterns_to_follow": "Hexagonal architecture for each service: domain logic in the center, Redis/WebSocket/HTTP as adapters. Event interfaces defined as TypeScript types in a shared schema package. All Redis operations wrapped in a repository abstraction so the Lua scripts can be tested independently. Use the state machine pattern for BidWindow — never check state with raw string comparisons.",
    "pitfalls_to_avoid": [
      "DO NOT use Redis WATCH/MULTI/EXEC for the CAS — it's optimistic and retries under contention. Lua scripts are the correct primitive for guaranteed atomic CAS.",
      "DO NOT store bid window state in Postgres — the 500 concurrent windows with 30 couriers each means up to 15,000 write attempts in 15 seconds. Postgres will choke on row-level lock contention.",
      "DO NOT rely on WebSocket delivery as the sole confirmation channel — mobile networks are unreliable. Always have a pull-based fallback (polling endpoint or push notification).",
      "DO NOT use setTimeout/setInterval in application code for the 15-second timeout — use the Redis sorted set approach. Application timers die with the process; Redis survives restarts.",
      "DO NOT let the Timeout Scheduler and Bid Processor race on the same job without the Lua script mediating — both must go through the same atomic CAS to prevent double-assignment.",
      "DO NOT fan out bid offers to couriers who are already in active bid windows without a cap — you'll create a winner-take-all effect where top-rated couriers are overwhelmed and everyone else gets nothing."
    ]
  },

  "escalations": [],

  "confidence": {
    "level": 88,
    "high_confidence_areas": [
      "Redis Lua CAS is the correct concurrency primitive for first-accept-wins at this scale",
      "WebSocket fan-out with pub/sub backplane handles the 15K connection requirement",
      "Ephemeral (Redis) + durable (Postgres) state separation is the right call for a 15-second window",
      "Sorted-set polling for timeouts is more reliable than keyspace notifications",
      "The state machine (OPEN → CLAIMED | EXPIRED) is complete — no missing states"
    ],
    "low_confidence_areas": [
      "Exact Redis Sentinel failover impact — would need load testing to validate the 5-10 job loss estimate during failover",
      "Mobile WebSocket reconnection behavior under real cellular conditions — may need MQTT as a more resilient transport",
      "Optimal bid_slots cap per courier — needs empirical tuning based on actual courier behavior data"
    ],
    "assumptions": [
      "Single geographic region deployment (no multi-datacenter requirement)",
      "30 couriers per zone is a soft average — system should handle spikes to 100 without redesign",
      "Courier mobile app can maintain a persistent WebSocket connection (acceptable battery trade-off)",
      "Redis single-instance throughput (~100K ops/sec) is sufficient for 500 concurrent windows — math checks out: 500 windows × 30 couriers = 15K CAS attempts over 15 seconds ≈ 1K ops/sec, well within limits"
    ]
  }
}
